Project Overview: E-Commerce Product Recommendation Network Analysis

This project analyzes a product co-interaction network
built from the Retailrocket e-commerce dataset, which
contains real user behavioral data (views, add-to-carts,
and purchases) collected from a live e-commerce
website. Products serve as nodes in the network,
and edges connect two products when they are
frequently interacted with by the same users, forming
a product recommendation network. Each product carries
categorical attributes derived from the site's category
hierarchy, including product category, category depth (top-level
vs. niche), and dominant interaction type (view-heavy
vs. purchase-heavy). The project computes both degree
centrality and eigenvector centrality for every product
node, then compares these centrality distributions across
categorical groups using statistical tests such as
the Kruskal-Wallis test and post-hoc pairwise comparisons.
The analysis aims to reveal whether certain product
categories occupy more central positions in the recommendation
network — for example, whether broadly popular categories
act as hubs connecting niche subcategories, or whether
purchase-driven products exhibit higher eigenvector centrality
than browse-only products. The project is implemented
in Python using NetworkX, pandas, and scipy,
delivered as a Jupyter Notebook, and hosted on GitHub.
